thread.title: Top 25 roundup: Georgia Tech stuns Florida State on last play

title: Top 25 roundup: Georgia Tech stuns Florida State on last play
text:
Royals defeat Blue Jays 4-3 to reach... 
Florida State drove the ball to the 46-yard line after a 22-yard reception by Dalvin Cook and a 9-yard reception by Jesus Wilson set up a game-winning 56-yard field goal try by Roberto Aguayo. 
But the interior of the Georgia Tech line blocked the ball and it rolled over to Austin, who picked it up and realized the play was live. Austin had blockers in front of them and cut across the field and down the sidelines, outrunning the final Florida State defender at the 5 to score the winning points. 
No. 1 Ohio State 49, Rutgers 7 
PISCATAWAY, N.J. -- Making his first start of the season for top-ranked Ohio State, J.T. Barrett passed for 223 yards and three touchdowns and ran for 101 yards on 13 carries and two more touchdowns as the Buckeyes rolled past the Scarlet Knights. 
The defending national champions have won 21 straight games, the longest active streak in the nation. 
Ohio State's Ezekiel Elliott, the Big Ten's leading rusher, ran for 142 yards on 19 carries and two scores. 
No. 2 Baylor 45, Iowa State 27 
WACO, Texas -- The Bears raced to a big first-quarter lead despite a drenched playing field, then sloshed the rest of the way to a victory over the Cyclones. 
The wet field and ball seemed to affect Baylor quarterback Seth Russell, who completed just 16 of 37 passes for 197 yards. But he threw two touchdown passes and ran for 64 yards and a score to help keep Baylor afloat and alive in the College Football Playoff race. 
Russell also suffered a fractured bone in his neck. Bears coach Art Briles told ESPN that he expects Russell to be out for a while but will know more after Russell sees the specialist. 
USC 42, No. 3 Utah 24 
LOS ANGELES -- Sparked by the defensive gems of linebacker Cameron Smith, the Trojans knocked the Utes from the unbeaten ranks. 
Smith intercepted three passes, including one that he brought back 54 yards for a touchdown. It was the first time a USC player had made three interceptions in a game since 1991 when safety Jason Oliver accomplished the feat. 
USC's defense contained Devontae Booker, who entered the game ranked 10th nationally at 130.5 rushing yards per game. Booker rushed for just 62 yards on 14 carries. 
No. 5 LSU 48, Western Kentucky 2 0 
BATON ROUGE, La. -- Jamal Adams, a safety playing on a special teams unit that ranked 114th out of 128 in special teams efficiency, forced a fumble on a third-quarter kickoff to spark a frenzied stretch that saw the Tigers score three touchdowns in less than five minutes to put away the Hilltoppers. 
LSU quarterback Brandon Harris outdueled Hilltopper quarterback Brandon Doughty -- the nation's second leading passer -- with a career-high 286 yards and three touchdowns to three receivers. 
Leonard Fournette rushed for 150 yards, giving him nine straight 100-yard games and tying the LSU school record. 
No. 6 Clemson 58, Miami 0 
MIAMI GARDENS, Fla. -- The Tigers jumped out early and led 42-0 at the half and recorded their biggest victory margin since an 82-24 rout of Wake Forest in 1981, their national championship season. 
The Hurricanes fell to 4-3 in absorbing the worst defeat in the history of their program, which started in 1925. 
The Tigers scored touchdowns on their first four possessions to take a 28-0 lead early in the second quarter and had 180 yards in total offense by that point. Deshaun Watson was 12-for-13 passing for 113 yards and a touchdown up to then and had a 63-yard run to set up Clemson's second score. 
No. 7 Michigan State 52, Indians 26 
EAST LANSING, Mich. -- Connor Cook threw for a career-high 398 yards and tied a career best with four touchdown passes to lead the Spartans. 
The senior came up 2 yards shy of the school record while completing 30 of 52 passes for the Spartans, who were coming off their miraculous last-play victory over archrival Michigan. 
R.J. Shelton caught six passes for 76 yards and two scores, and Aaron Burbridge hauled in eight passes for 128 yards and a touchdown for the Spartans. 
No. 8 Alabama 19, Tennessee 14 
TUSCALOOSA, Ala. -- Derrick Henry ran 14 yards for a touchdown with 2:24 left in the game and the Crimson Tide escaped with a win. 
Tennessee had taken the lead by going 75 yards in four plays to make it 14-13 on Jalen Hurd's 12-yard touchdown run with 5:49 remaining. 
Tennessee had an opportunity to pull out the win with two minutes remaining, but Ryan Anderson sacked Joshua Dobbs, whose fumble was recovered by A'Shawn Robinson. 
No. 14 Oklahoma State 58, Kansas 10 
STILLWATER, Okla. -- Mason Rudolph passed for 300 yards and a touchdown, taking a seat early. J.W. Walsh, Rudolph's backup, who is often utilized in a special package near the goal line, ran for three touchdowns and threw for two more. 
Earlier in the day, a woman drove a car into a homecoming crowd, killing four and injuring score s more during what the school hails as "America's Greatest Homecoming Celebration." 
"We really talked a lot about whether to play the game," Oklahoma State president Burns Hargis said. "The decision was finally made that we're going to play and we're going to remember the victims at the game. We're going to move forward, but we will remember what's happened today." 
No. 17 Oklahoma 63, Texas Tech 27 
NORMAN, Okla. -- Samaje Perine and Joe Mixon combined for 355 yards rushing and six touchdowns Saturday as the Sooners beat the Red Raiders. 
There was plenty of talk going into the game about the matchup of Sooners quarterback Baker Mayfield with his former team, but that storyline took a backseat to Oklahoma's running game. 
Perine, a sophomore, ran for 201 yards and four scores while Mixon, a redshirt freshman, ran for 154 yards and two scores. 
No. 19 Toledo 51, Massachusetts 35 
FOXBOROUGH, Mass. -- The Rockets spotted the Minutemen an 18-point halftime lead but roared back with a huge second half and to post the victory. 
The Rockets, who scored 56 straight points to wipe out a 6-0 deficit against Eastern Michigan the previous week, trailed the Minutemen 28-10 at the half and then scored 38 consecutive points in the first 20:29 of the second half to blow it open. 
Philip Ely, who threw three interceptions in the first half, fired five touchdown passes, four of them in the second half -- with three of those coming during the third quarter when Toledo held UMass to one first down. 
No. 21 Houston 59, Central Florida 10 
ORLANDO, Fla. -- Houston scored on seven straight possessions and racked up 595 yards of offense in a rout of Central Florida. 
Kenneth Farrow had 13 carries for 170 yards and three touchdowns. The Cougars are 7-0 for the fourth time in school history. Central Florida is 0-8. 
Houston's Greg Ward Jr., who entered the game seventh in the nation in total offense, accounted for 256 yards of offense and two touchdowns. 
No. 23 Duke 45, Virginia Tech, 43, 4OT 
BLACKSBURG, Va. -- Thomas Sirk passed for 270 yards and four touchdowns, and added a team-high 109 rushing yards in the Blue Devils quadruple-overtime victory. 
Sirk scored the game-winning points on a 2-point conversion run. That play came after his 25-yard touchdown pass to Erich Schneider in the first four-overtime game in ACC history. 
Duke's Max McCaffery had six catches for 94 yards and two touchdowns. 
No. 24 Mississippi 23, No. 15 Texas A&M 3 
OXFORD, Miss. -- A week after suffering a disappointing loss to Memphis, the Rebels bounced back against the Aggies. 
Laremy Tunsil returned to the lineup at offensive tackle and the Rebels' running game showed dramatic improvement even though it settled for field goals in the first half. 
Texas A&M quarterback Kyle Allen was held to 90 yards in the first half. 
No. 25 Pittsburgh 23, Syracuse 20 
SYRACUSE, N.Y. -- A 12-yard pass from punter Ryan Winslow to middle linebacker Matt Galambos kept alive a drive that ended with the winning field goal as Pittsburgh outlasted Syracuse. 
Set up to punt on fourth-and-7 from their own 48, the Panthers snapped the ball to Winslow, who raced to the edge of the line of scrimmage and floated a pass to Galambos, who rumbled to the Syracuse 40. 
Pittsburgh moved to the Orange 6 before kicker Chris Blewitt drilled a 24-yard field goal on the last play of the game.
